<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-06-03T12:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-06-03T12:36:00-05:00" n="999" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d999">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.93/31.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-06-03T11:00:00-06:36">
                                    <hi rend="italic">June 3, 1913—11 a.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>268. The Chinese Chargé d’Affaires has requested, in the name of his
                            Government, that American consuls in disturbed districts be instructed
                            to extend protection to Chinese citizens when in distress or danger. I
                            await instructions.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Henry Lane Wilson</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>